INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '581fdf11-105b-46a7-bad6-1a46f1ebd435',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Snowflake Clustering Keys — How Partition Pruning Actually Works$escape$,
  $escape$Snowflake automatically divides tables into micro-partitions (~50–500 MB compressed), storing per-column min/max metadata for each. At query time, the optimizer skips micro-partitions whose metadata ranges don't overlap your WHERE predicates — no manual partitioning DDL required.

The problem: rows loaded in arbitrary order cluster naturally on insertion sequence, not your access patterns. If queries filter on `event_date` but rows arrived out of order, Snowflake must scan far more micro-partitions than necessary.

Fix this by defining a clustering key:

```sql
ALTER TABLE events CLUSTER BY (event_date, user_id);
```

Snowflake's Automatic Clustering service then continuously re-sorts micro-partitions in the background. Diagnose effectiveness with `SYSTEM$CLUSTERING_INFORMATION` — the `average_depth` value is the key metric: depth of 1 means perfect clustering; anything above ~3 signals degraded pruning.

Practical rules: cluster only on high-cardinality columns you filter frequently; truncate raw timestamps to DATE to avoid exploding distinct values; and suspend recluster on cold tables — Automatic Clustering consumes credits on every reorganization pass.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Add a clustering key aligned to your dominant query predicate
ALTER TABLE events CLUSTER BY (event_date, user_id);

-- Inspect clustering health — target average_depth close to 1
SELECT SYSTEM$CLUSTERING_INFORMATION('events', '(event_date, user_id)');

-- Confirm pruning in the query plan (look for partitionsScanned vs partitionsTotal)
EXPLAIN
SELECT user_id, event_type, COUNT(*)
FROM events
WHERE event_date BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-03-31'
GROUP BY 1, 2;

-- Suspend auto-clustering on cold/archive tables to avoid unnecessary credit spend
ALTER TABLE events SUSPEND RECLUSTER;$escape$,
