INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ba3ea514-1a62-44fb-9b40-d2da443d8ca3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Snowflake Monitoring — Query History, Cost Dashboards, and Slow Query Alerts$escape$,
  $escape$Snowflake's ACCOUNT_USAGE schema is your primary observability layer. QUERY_HISTORY view exposes execution_time, bytes_scanned, credits_used_cloud_services, and partitions_scanned for every query run in the last 365 days — with up to 45 minutes of latency. For real-time inspection, use INFORMATION_SCHEMA.QUERY_HISTORY() (last 7 days, ~1 second latency).

For cost dashboards, join QUERY_HISTORY with WAREHOUSE_METERING_HISTORY on warehouse_name and start_time to attribute credit burn to specific warehouses and users. Filter on execution_status = 'SUCCESS' and credits_used_cloud_services > 0 to surface expensive metadata operations.

For slow query alerts, schedule a task using Snowflake Tasks + a Stored Procedure that queries QUERY_HISTORY WHERE execution_time > 60000 (milliseconds) AND start_time >= DATEADD(minute, -15, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP()). Push results to a notification integration via SYSTEM$SEND_EMAIL() or a Slack webhook. Pair with QUERY_PROFILE (accessible via UI or REST) to drill into operator-level bottlenecks like remote disk spills or partition pruning inefficiencies.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Top 10 slowest queries in the last 24 hours with credit cost
SELECT
    query_id,
    query_text,
    user_name,
    warehouse_name,
    ROUND(execution_time / 1000, 2)        AS exec_seconds,
    ROUND(credits_used_cloud_services, 4)  AS cloud_credits,
    partitions_scanned,
    partitions_total
FROM snowflake.account_usage.query_history
WHERE start_time >= DATEADD(hour, -24, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP())
  AND execution_status = 'SUCCESS'
ORDER BY execution_time DESC
LIMIT 10;$escape$,
  $escape$sql$escape$,
